The morphological characteristics (hydrodynamic radius to radius of gyration ratio, Rg/Rh
                     ; fractal dimension, df
                     ) of the prepared nanosystems obtained by SLS in the day of preparation (t = 0 days). Samples at pH = 6.0 were measured at 25 °C, while samples at pH = 4.2 were measured at 42 °C.

ce:section.ce:para:
In order to clarify whether the newly-developed nanosystems still exhibit the pH-responsiveness from the PDMAEMA block, apart from the high positive cargo (Table 1
                        ), we studied the effect of different pH values in their physicochemical behavior (Figure 1, S4). According to the results, the systems exhibited a pH-induced ζ-potential change (Fig. 1
                        ). In acidic conditions (pH = 4.2), the majority of the systems exhibited an increase of ζ-potential, while all the systems presented a decrease of ζ-potential in physiological pH. Similar shifts have been observed also in the systems of previous studies, where PDMAEMA-b-PLMA copolymer was used (Chountoulesi et al. 2019). These shifts can be attributed to the free PDMAEMA blocks, because the PDMAEMA block, being a weak polybase, behaves as a weak cationic polyelectrolyte under different pH conditions. PDMAEMA tertiary amine groups are fully protonated at acidic pH (pH ≪ pKa) and partially protonated at neutral pH, yielding the observed ζ-potential shifts (Chrysostomou and Pispas, 2018; Sprouse et al. 2016). Three systems presented a decrease of ζ-potential in citrate buffer, however they still exhibited high positive charge (> +30 mV) (Fig. 1). Regarding the size and size distribution (Figure S4), no significant changes were observed in all the systems, apart from an increase of PDI after pH decrease.

The thermal properties of GMO-based nanosystems in the presence of the various polymeric stabilizers were investigated using microcalorimetry and high resolution ultrasound spectroscopy. Fig. 5
                           a reports the thermograms from mDSC, in which a main endothermic transition is clearly observable in the temperature range 15–20 °C for all samples. This transition can be recognised as the temperature-induced conversion of lamellar Lβ to the lamellar Lα mesophase (Efrat et al 2009; Fraser and Separovi, 2009), and it represents the main thermal transition of GMO in aqueous dispersions that is observable by mDSC (Chountoulesi et al. 2020). The other thermal transitions of GMO bilayer, occurring at higher temperatures (e.g., lamellar to discontinuous cubic mesophases, QL
                           ), being less energetic, are barely appreciable. As previously reported for P407, PDMAEMA-b-PLMA or MPOx1 used alone (GMO to polymeric stabilizer ratio of 9:1) (Chountoulesi et al. 2021), a single well-defined transition at around 15 °C was observed in the presence of TPP-QPDMAEMA-b-PLMA, suggesting that all these polymeric stabilizers do not influence markedly the main lamellar transition of GMO in water. However, it can be postulated that they can be inserted in the liquid crystalline phase of GMO as demonstrated for P407 (Dong et al. 2012), thereby stabilizing cubic structures. A broadening of the signal related to the lamellar transition of GMO bilayer was observed in systems containing the second stabilizer (PEO-b-PCL H1 or MPOx1) in addition to TPP-QPDMAEMA-b-PLMA. Indeed, multiple endothermic events can occur in the temperature range 15–20 °C, suggesting that the internal organization of GMO bilayer has been changed. This can be confirmed by the determined transition temperatures of the systems prepared with the co-assembly of two stabilizers that are slightly higher (∼18 °C) than those calculated for systems containing only TPP-QPDMAEMA-b-PLMA as stabilizer (∼15 °C). The enthalpy values associated to the transition are comparable among systems studied (0.100–0.120 J/g of solution). Only for the system stabilized with the co-assembly of TPP-QPDMAEMA-b-PLMA with MPOx1, a slightly higher enthalpy value (∼0.200 J/g of solution) was determined (Table 3
                           ), probably related to the structural characteristics of MPOx1, that differ from the others (i.e., a gradient block copolymer can possibly induce a more packed lipid bilayer structure) (Chountoulesi et al. 2021). The thermal behaviour was also studied using HR-US by recording ultrasound speed signals over temperature (Fig. 5b). According to this technique, the transition can be recognised as a deviation of the signal from the linearity. Sound speed decreases intrinsically over temperature but the occurring of a transition in the material affects its compressibility and density, thereby affecting sound speed (Bonacucina et al. 2016). The deviation of the sound speed can be observed in the same temperature range in which mDSC signals were recorded and it is more evident for the systems stabilized with a single stabilizer. Transition temperatures determined from HR-US are reported in Table 3 and are in accordance with those determined from mDSC.
